<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-756-604  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 756 604.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Sept 11 1989 v3 n37 p52(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>NIST pay project hits mark, firm says. (National Institute ofStandards and Technology)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Levine, Arnold S.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The National Institute of Standards and Technology's (NIST)personnel demonstration project, sponsored by the Office ofPersonnel Management (OPM), may serve as a model of successfulpay/performance methods.andP;  The NIST project is scheduled to run forfive years, after four years the General Accounting Office (GAO)will submit a final report to Congress with recommendations.andP;  NISTofficials believe that the project's success can be attributed tothe streamlining and automation of job classifications, use ofpaid advertising, and efficiency of the personnel andadministrative systems.andP;  University Research Corp (URC) evaluatedthe project's first year which began Jan 1, 1988, and hascontracted to report on NIST annually.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   University Research Corp. (reports).andO;Topic:     United States. National Institute of Standards and TechnologyPersonnel ManagementAutomationEvaluationSalary.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>